@NODE Installation "Installation"

INSTALLATION

@{CODE}
 - Copy the file 'vdisk.device' to your DEVS: directory .
   NEVER CHANGE THE NAME OF THIS FILE !!!

 - Copy the support commands CleanRamDisk, DeleteRamDisk, VDStat to your
   C: directory or whatever you like. You may also copy the .info files.

 - If you have OS 2.1 or higher, copy the file VD0 to your DEVS:DOSDrivers
   directory. You may change the name of this file to whatever you want.
   You may edit this file to change some parameters of the recoverable RAM
   disk, such as its maximum size. (see below)

 - If you have OS 2.0 , join the file VD0.mountlist to your DEVS:MountList
   file. You may change the name of the mountlist entry to whatever you want.
   You may also edit the mountlist record to change some parameters of the
   recoverable RAM disk (see below). Make sure you do not have another
   entry with the same name in your mountlist (especially if you use the
   old asdg-ram).
   Add a 'Mount VD0:' command to your S:User-Startup. If you have 1 Mb or
   less memory, it may be wise to put this command at the beginning of your
   Startup-Sequence to minimize the risk of recovery failures.

 - If you still have OS 1.x, well... It's time to upgrade !

 - If you want to make use of the new automount/autoboot features, get THOR's
   LoadModule command from Aminet and install it. Add a command line like:
   'LoadModule DEVS:vdisk.device REVERSE' to your Startup-Sequence right
   before SetPatch. Refer to the LoadModule documentation for the available
   options and for interoperation with the OS3.5/OS3.9 AmigaOS ROM Updates.

 - After that, reboot your Amiga. If all is OK, you should see an icon named
   VD-RAM-00 on your Workbench. To set a different volume name, add a
   'Relabel' command to your User-Startup after the mount command.

   NOTE : If you are upgrading from an earlier version of vdisk.device, you
          *MUST* issue a 'DeleteRamDisk' command on all active units before
          rebooting the system, or unexpected side effects may happen.
          See the support commands below.
@{BODY}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Configuration "Mountfile Parameters"

CHANGING MOUNTFILE PARAMETERS

@{CODE}
  WARNING : Changing any other MountFile parameter than those listed below may
            cause the vdisk.device to cease to function and to wake up the
            GURU with recoverable alert AN_VDBadStartup ($50000005) !
            After changing ANY parameter of an already active unit, you MUST
            issue a 'DeleteRamDisk' command on it before rebooting the system,
            or unexpected things may happen. This applies also for volatile
	    units.

 - @{B}DOS device name@{UB}: Unlike the original asdg.vdisk.device, you can give any
   name you want to the recoverable RAM disk. Just change the name of the
   mountfile (OS 2.1+) or the mountlist entry (OS 2.0). The default name is
   VD0 . It is recommended that the last character be a digit equal to the 
   unit number.

 - @{B}Unit@{UB}: This is the device unit number. You can have several recoverable
   RAM disks by having different mountfiles with different values for this
   keyword. Valid numbers are 0 to 15, giving a possible total of 16 units.

 - @{B}Flags@{UB}: Different options may be selected here. You combine them by adding
   their respective value (ex. to enable autocleaning and allocretry, use
   Flags = 0x3). Note that some combinations like Volatile and Bootable are
   rather pointless.
   · A Flags value of 1 (bit 0 set) will enable autocleaning on the corresponding
   unit. This means that the memory used by the ram disk will automatically
   decrease when you delete files in it. This also implies that you cannot use
   tools like DiskSalv to recover the deleted files. If autocleaning is not
   set, you must use the CleanRamDisk support command to free memory after
   deleting files. Cleaning may still happen if the system runs low on memory.
   It is recommended that you keep AutoCleaning enabled unless you plan to use
   DiskCopy, DMS or other utilities that bypass the filesystem when writing
   to the vdisk unit.
   · A flags value of 2 (bit 1 set) will enable allocretry. This causes the
   vdisk unit to retry failed memory allocations with less restrictive
   conditions than those specified in the BufMemType parameter. The allocation
   retry will use any public memory available. This is only useful if you have
   set specific memory requirements in the BufMemType parameter (to force use
   of 16 bit fast ram for ex.) and don't want an error to be returned if this
   specific memory type is exhausted.
   · A flags value of 4 (bit 2 set, V3+) will cause the vdisk unit to be lost
   if any error is detected at recovery time. This was the default behaviour
   on vdisk.device V2. With version 3, the default is now to keep the unit
   alive if the only errors present are sector data checksums. The driver will
   return an error anyways on an attempt to read a corrupted sector. You should
   set this flag only if you want to retain the V2 behaviour.
   · A flags value of 8 (bit 3 set, V3.3+) will enable automounting of this unit
   if the vdisk.device has been installed as a resident module, otherwise it will
   be ignored. Automount units are mounted by AmigaDOS before execution of the
   Startup-Sequence and will appear in the early startup menu.
   · A flags value of 16 (Hex $10, bit 4 set, V3.3+) enables autobooting from
   this unit. This must be set together with the automount bit or it will be
   ignored. It will then be possible to boot the system from this vdisk unit
   through the early startup menu.
   · A flags value of 32 (Hex $20, bit 5 set, V3.4+) disables any cleaning of
   the unit, even in low memory conditions. The only way to reclaim memory from
   the unit is to use the CleanRamDisk command with the FORCE keyword. You
   should set this bit for units that are directly written to at the device
   level, such as virtual floppies used to extract DMS or ADF files.
   · A flags value of 64 (Hex $40, bit 6 set, V3.5+) declares a volatile unit
   that will be wiped clean on system reboot. Such units may be used as a
   replacement for the system RAM: disk.
   · All other bits are currently reserved and should be left cleared.

 - @{B}BootPri@{UB} (V3.3): Selects the boot priority for autobooting units, ignored
   otherwise.

 - @{B}BlockSize@{UB} (V3): Sets the physical sector size in bytes. The values 512, 1024
   and 2048 are valid, the default being 512. This keyword may not be accepted
   by old versions of the mount command and/or FastFileSystem.

 - @{B}HighCyl, Surfaces, BlocksPerTrack@{UB}: These are used to specify the maximum size
   the vdisk unit is allowed to use. When this size is reached, you will get a
   'Volume is full' requester. Note that unlike RAD, vdisk.device does only
   allocate memory when you write files into it.
   Starting with V3, you may specify any geometry here provided the LowCyl
   keyword is set to 0 (partitioning is not supported) and the internal limit
   of 65535 VTracks of 32 sectors each is not exceeded (This corresponds to
   1 Gb at 512 bytes/sector). So it is now possible to mount a vdisk unit
   with the same geometry as a floppy disk for example.
   Do not set the maximum size too high ! If you run out of memory before
   filling the vdisk unit, you will get a 'write error' requester and the
   filesystem on the volume might become corrupt !!!
   The recommended maximum size is one fourth of your total FAST RAM.
   The byte size is obtained as (HighCyl +1) * Surfaces * BlocksPerTrack * BlockSize.
   The device rounds this up internally to an integer number of 32 sectors VTracks,
   that are allocated on demand when written to.
   The default values in the supplied mountlist (HighCyl = 63, BlocksPerTrack = 32,
   Surfaces = 1, BlockSize = 512) thus correspond to a maximum size of 1024 Kb.

 - @{B}Buffers@{UB}: This is the number of buffers used by the File System to speed up
   disk accesses. With a RAM disk, any speedup would be marginal, so there's
   no point adding more buffers than 10.

 - @{B}BufMemType@{UB}: Strictly speaking, this is the type of memory used by the
   File System for its internal buffers. For vdisk.device, it also affects
   the type of memory allocated to store data you write into it.
   You can combine different attributes by adding their respective values.
   A value of 0x1 (MEMF_PUBLIC) means public memory (shared and non virtual)
   and is always enforced by the device, regardless if this bit is set in
   the BufMemType value or not.
   0x2 (MEMF_CHIP) is chip memory (not recommended).
   0x4 (MEMF_FAST) is fast memory.
   0x100 (MEMF_LOCAL) is motherboard memory that should survive a reset. You
   can try to set this flag if vdisk loses its content after reboot.
   0x200 (MEMF_24BITDMA) is memory accessible via 24 bit addresses. This
   can be 16 or 32 bit RAM though.
   0x400 (MEMF_KICK) is memory that can be used at boot time. This is only
   defined in KickStart 3.0+.
   The default value is 0x5 which means public fast memory.

 - @{B}DosType@{UB}: The type of File System used. Possible values are :
    0x444f5300 : Old File System. Slow and not really needed since vdisk.device
                 has its own checksums.
    0x444f5301 : pre 2.1 Fast File System.
    0x444f5302 : International Old File System. OS 2.1 + only.
    0x444f5303 : International Fast File System. The recommanded default for OS 2.1+
    0x444f5304 : Directory Caching Old File System. OS 3.0 +
    0x444f5305 : Directory Caching Fast File System. OS 3.0 +
   International mode may be used if you run OS 2.1 or higher. Directory Caching
   is not recommanded since it is slower for anything but floppy disks.
   You may use other filesystems like SFS with some restrictions: first, you will
   have to explicitely format the unit with the Format command for first use and
   second, no reclamation of unused space can be performed as the vdisk.device
   does not know the filesystem structure.

 - @{B}Activate@{UB}: Instructs the mount command to start the device immediately when
   set to 1. If you set it to 0, you must add some command in your Startup
   that accesses the unit to start it really.
@{BODY}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Commands "Support Commands"

SUPPORT COMMANDS


 @{B}CleanRamDisk@{UB}


 This command is used to force a vdisk unit to free deleted file space. It
is generally not needed with autocleaning units.
This command may be used from Workbench (but tooltypes are currently ignored).
Select the virtual disk icon, then double-click on the CleanRamDisk icon.

@{CODE}
  Usage : CleanRamDisk DEVICE,UNIT/K/N,NOFREECHIP/S,REBUILD/S,FREEBOOT/S,FORCE/S

  DEVICE:     This is the AmigaDOS device name (ex. VD0: )
  UNIT:	      Alternatively to the AmigaDOS name, you may specify the unit
	      number (ex. UNIT 0)
  NOFREECHIP: When BufMemType is set to 1, CleanRamDisk normally attempts to
              free some CHIP memory by relocating virtual tracks located in
              CHIP RAM to FAST RAM. This switch inhibits this behaviour.
  REBUILD:    When a vdisk unit has read errors on it (generally caused by some
	      bad software that writes over someone else's memory), it may be
	      lost at the next reboot (which in this case may come soon).
	      This switch forces a rebuild of all internal checksums so that
	      the unit will be kept alive after reset. Some data will still be
	      bad, but you should be able to save most of it.
  FREEBOOT:   If something has been written in the RAM disk's boot blocks
	      (unused at this time), virtual track 0 will be locked in memory.
	      This switch will mark the boot blocks as free, thus enabling the
	      cleaning routine to flush track 0 out.
  FORCE:      Force cleaning of units which have the NOCLEAN flag set. (V3.4+)
@{BODY}


 @{B}DeleteRamDisk@{UB}


 This command deletes a virtual disk unit entirely (as RemRAD for RAD). All
memory used is freed and the File System is inhibited, causing the volume to be
shown as BUSY on the Workbench.
 This command may be used from Workbench. Select the virtual disk icon, then
double-click on the DeleteRamDisk icon. A requester will ask you for confir-
mation.
 You @{B}MUST@{UB} use this command when you change the mountfile parameters of
an active unit, even a volatile one. You must also delete all active units when
you upgrade to a newer version of vdisk.device. 

@{CODE}
  Usage : DeleteRamDisk DEVICE,UNIT/K/N

  DEVICE: This is the AmigaDOS device name (ex. VD0: )
  UNIT:	  Alternatively to the AmigaDOS name, you may specify the unit number
	  (ex. UNIT 0)
@{BODY}


 @{B}VDStat@{UB}


 This command is used to get information about a virtual disk unit that
failed to recover its data after reboot. It is mainly intended for diagnostics,
so it cannot be used from Workbench.
 Recovery error 2 (Root Structure not found) will always be reported the first
time the device is loaded after power-up.

@{CODE}
  Usage : VDStat DEVICE,UNIT/K/N,FULL/S

  DEVICE: This is the AmigaDOS device name (ex. VD0: )
  UNIT:	  Alternatively to the AmigaDOS name, you may specify the unit number
	  (ex. UNIT 0)
  FULL:	  This switch causes more information to be displayed. It is mainly
	  used for debugging purposes.
@{BODY}

  Recovery error codes:

@{CODE}
  1 (Deleted Unit): This will show after reboot when a unit is deleted by
    the DeleteRamDisk command.
  2 (Root structure not found): The root structure which keeps pointers to vdisk
    units was not found at all, either by its resident tag entry in ExecBase
    KickTagPtr chain or by blind reverse memory reallocation. This is normal at
    power-up. If it shows up on a subsequent warm boot, its most likely cause
    is the memory being wiped-out, either by a bad program or by 'creative'
    hardware that falsely reports its memory as being reset proof (see the
    @{"known problems" link Problems} section.
    This error implies the loss of all units.
  3 (Bad Root Structure Checksum): The Root Structure has been corrupted.
    Bad program or memory around ! All units were lost.
  4 (Bad Sector CheckSum): A sector of an active unit had an invalid checksum.
    With version 3, this will only cause the unit to be removed (and this error
    to be reported) if bit 2 of the MountFile Flags is set. Indicates either a
    bad program, or a hardware memory problem.
  5 (Track not found): The header section of an active VTrack was corrupted.
    Most likely caused by a bad program vomitting over innocent memory.
  6 (Reallocation Failure): Memory used by an active unit couldn't be
    reallocated with AllocAbs(). This is most likely caused by interference with
    some other reset resistant software. Make sure you always start all this
    type of software in the same relative order. It may also happen if the
    maximum size allowed to vdisk units is too big compared to available memory
    and vdisk data got allocated at low addresses that may interfere with early
    boot allocations. You might try to install vdisk.device as a resident module
    with Thomas Richter's LoadModule command so that the memory used by vdisk
    units can be reclaimed as early as possible.
  7 (Unit Structure not found): An active Unit structure header got trashed, most
    likely by bad software.
  8 (Bad Unit Structure Checksum): Corrupted unit structure, most likely by a bad
    program.
  9 (Bad Root Structure Version): The version ID of the root structure did not
    match that of the device itself.
  10 (Unknown Error): How did you get this one ?
@{BODY}

@ENDNODE
@NODE History "Version History"

CHANGES

@{CODE}
 @{B}V 3.8@{UB}
      - Fixed illegal memory accesses during initialization of big volumes with
	bitmap extension blocks. Thanks to Dale Frameli for the bug report.

 @{B}V 3.7@{UB}
      - Fixed a nasty data corruption bug in the unit cleaning routine.

 @{B}V 3.6@{UB}
      - Fixed Expunge and Init routines to allow removal and reloading of the
	device without system reboot. Also, a delayed expunge would have crashed
	due to mismatched stack usage.
      - Official release of vdisk V3.

 @{B}V 3.5 beta (internal)@{UB}
      - Added support for VOLATILE units that will be wiped clean on system
	reboot like the system RAM: disk.

 @{B}V 3.4 beta@{UB}
      - Added NOCLEAN flag to completely disable memory reclamation for vdisk
	units used as virtual floppies.
      - New AmigaDOS units now get preallocated bitmap blocks for compatibility
	with the new FFS2.

 @{B}V 3.3 beta@{UB}
      - Added support for AUTOMOUNT and BOOTABLE vdisk units. This requires
	the vdisk.device to be installed as a resident module with THOR's
	LoadModule command.
      - Some extended trackdisk commands are now accepted as a compatibility
	kludge for broken software like DMS that can't be bothered to fall
	back to the normal commands. They are not officially supported and
	should otherwise not be used.
      - TD_GETGEOMETRY now returns the AmigaDOS faked geometry in CHS fields
	and the real number of available sectors in the TotalSectors field
	(some of which might not be available to AmigaDOS).

 @{B}V 3.2 beta@{UB}
      - Corrected a stupid bug in the unit checksum routine, which read
	past the end of the unit structure (yuck!).

 @{B}V 3.1 beta@{UB}
      -	Major changes. Internal VTrack size is now 32 sectors which can
	themselves use sizes of 512, 1024 or 2048 bytes. The device now
	also accepts AmigaDOS faked geometries (so a unit can look like
	a floppy for example) as long as LowCyl is 0, SectorPerBlocks
	is 1 and Reserved is 2. The filesystem root block should be
	correctly placed as well.
      - Initialization recovery checks reworked so they no longer reference
	memory not yet reallocated.
      - 'muFS' DosType is now recognized and supported, although the
	current multiuser.library only allows the MultiUserFileSystem
	on hard disk partitions.
      - NSCMD_DEVICEQUERY and TD_GETGEOMETRY commands are now supported.

 @{B}V 2.7@{UB}
      -	Fixed a stupid bug that caused crashes when odd unit numbers 
	were used on a 68000 system.

 @{B}V 2.6@{UB}
      - The kludge for safely using $C00000 memory has been entirely
	rewritten. It does no longer cause fragmentation of this
	memory.
      - The Root structure is now allocated in MEMF_KICK memory
	(MEMF_LOCAL for OS 2). This should help vdisk to survive
	reboot on systems with non autoconfig 32bit memory.
      - Added the allocretry Flags option.
      - vdisk will now allow memory flushing to occur when it
	tries to allocate more memory.

 @{B}V 2.5@{UB}
      - vdisk now retries failed memory allocations with MEMF_PUBLIC
	when BufMemType was set to allocate a specific type of
	memory. This should cause less write errors.
      - French doc included after numerous requests.

 @{B}V 2.4@{UB}
	First released version.
@{BODY}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Problems "Known Problems"

KNOWN PROBLEMS


 It seems that certain accelerator boards have 32 bit memory that does
not keep its content after a reset. This will cause vdisk to lose its
files.
 If this happens to you, try to set the BufMemType parameter to 0x400
(if you have OS 3+) or 0x100 (for OS 2) to prevent vdisk from using this
32 bit memory. Also don't set the allocretry bit in Flags.

@ENDNODE
